onergic agents sequentially, as some agents may demonstrate a prolonged elimination half-life.', 'Synergism', 'Naloxone', NULL, 'Major', NULL, 'DDInter', 'pharmacodynamic', NULL, 'https://ddinter2.scbdd.com/server/interact/5985/', '[1] Martin TG "Serotonin syndrome." Ann Emerg Med 28 (1996): 520-6[2] "Product Information. Nucynta (tapentadol)." PriCara Pharmaceuticals, Raritan, NJ.[3] Mason BJ, Blackburn KH "Possible serotonin syndrome associated with tramadol and sertraline coadministration." Ann Pharmacother 31 (1997): 175-7[4] Kesavan S, Sobala GM "Serotonin syndrome with fluoxetine plus tramadol." J R Soc Med 92 (1999): 474-5[5] "Product Information. Effexor (venlafaxine)." Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories, Philadelphia, PA.[6] "Product Information. Fetzima (levomilnacipran)." Forest Pharmaceuticals, St. Louis, MO.[7] Shakoor M, Ayub S, Ahad A, Ayub Z "Transient serotonin syndrome caused by concurrent use of tramadol and selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor." Am J Case Rep 15 (2014): 562-4[8] "Product Information. Viibryd (vilazodone)." Trovis Pharmaceuticals LLC, New Haven, CT.[9] Mittino D, Mula M, Monaco F "Serotonin syndrome associated with tramadol-sertraline coadministration." Clin Neuropharmacol 27 (2004): 150-1[10] "Venlafaxine + tramadol: serotonin syndrome." Prescrire Int 13 (2004): 57[11] Lantz MS, Buchalter EN, Giambanco V "Serotonin syndrome following the administration of tramadol with paroxetine." Int J Geriatr Psychiatry 13 (1998): 343-5[12] "Product Information. Pristiq (desvenlafaxine)." Wyeth Laboratories, Philadelphia, PA.[13] "Product Information. Savella (milnacipran)." Forest Pharmaceuticals, St. Louis, MO.[14] Gonzalez-Pinto A, Imaz H, De Heredia JL, Gutierrez M, Mico JA "Mania and tramadol-fluoxetine combination." Am J Psychiatry 158 (2001): 964-5[15] Lange-Asschenfeldt C, Weigmann H, Hiemke C, Mann K "Serotonin syndrome as a result of fluoxetine in a patient with tramadol abuse: plasma level-correlated symptomatology." J Clin Psychopharmacol